title: For Sale:  Franchi I-12 12 ga. with 24" Barrel & Advantage Timber Camo
postcontent:
Nice used shotgun with little wear. Super light and has an action that is as smooth as hot butter. Has Twin Shock Absorber recoil pad. 24" barrel and shoot 2 3/4" and 3" shells. Has fiber optic front sight.

Here is a REVIEW from the internet:
I had the chance to spend several days with the I-12 last summer on an incredible duck hunt in Uruguay. The variety of species and the sheer number of ducks were astounding. Bag limits there are liberal, so you can really burn through a lot of ammo. You need a gun that can take the sting out of high-brass duck loads, and the I-12's recoil reduction system did that with ease.

The first line of recoil reduction really comes from the I-12's Inertia Driven system. Here's how it works: Instead of having a heavy gas cylinder in the fore end, which adds weight and can make guns feel clubby, the I-12 doesn't rely on pistons or valves. The mechanically simple system features a free-floating bolt that compresses an inertia spring as the gun recoils. This, in turn, cycles the action. The result is a slender, lower-profile forend that really feels great—even for guys with smaller hands like me. And eliminating the big gas cylinder and hardware up front also gives these guns a nice balance—quick-pointing and smooth-swinging without feeling whippy.

An even bigger help toward reducing felt recoil is a unique, two-part recoil pad. The pad has a special gel insert, but unlike some recoil pad designs, this one is open on both sides, which allows the gel insert to deform outward to spread the kick over a much wider area.

When the gun is fired, the special rubber part of the pad maintains the pad's shape. At the same time, the gel insert starts to deform outward, spreading the recoil out and cutting down on all the shock to your shoulder. After compression, the gel insert returns to its original shape in a fraction of a second.

We burned through a lot of shotshells in the course of our trip. Moreover, the weather was unseasonably warm, so by mid-morning we were hunting in shirt-sleeves without the benefit of any extra padding from heavy coats. Despite all the shooting we did, my shoulder never got sore.

The I-12 I used came in a flat-black finish (a good all-purpose color choice), but for a few dollars more, these guns can also be purchased in Advantage Timber HD for turkey hunting, Advantage MAX-4 for waterfowling or traditional satin-finished walnut. All represent a great value, too.

title: For Trade:  SOC LLC DPMS AR15 IRAQ BRINGBACK
postcontent:
this is a DPMS AR15 semi-auto rifle in 5.56-.223 cal with heavy barrel 1-9 twist.
Flat top upper, internals are in nice shape, externally the rifle has lots of finish wear.
These rifles were the property of SOC LLC a private security contractor that provided guards on US bases in IRAQ.
These DPMS rifles were brought back to the US after the contract ended along with some wasr10/63 ak47 rifles and various bushmaster and american spirit rifles.

These rifles were then sold by SOC LLC to Century Arms who then sold them to various companies earlier this year. There are alot of discussions on various forums about these rifles, Do an internet search for DPMS or WASR 10 Iraq bringback rifle and you will find alot of interesting discussions.

The condition of these rifles obviously varies alot, The one i have has been carried quite abit but not fired a whole lot (at a guess)
These rifles were issused to mainly Ugandan guards working on US bases in IRAQ guarding checkpoints, chowhalls, portapottys ect 

These guns are quite unique in the fact that these will be the only modern surplus rifles used in the Iraq War and then sold to the public. Will they be a collectors item in 20 years? i dont know but if nothing else they will make a decent beater/truck rifle with a neat story.

I have the original furniture, G.I mag and dirty 3 point sling that came with this rifle, Its a flat top and did not come with the carry handle although i do have a replacement i could throw on it, I also have a new set of magpul furniture that i could add to a trade, I have removed pretty much all the damn sand and dirt from this rifle (hopefully that didnt ruin the collectors value haha)

title: For Sale:  BRNO CZ 98 .270 Win
postcontent:
FS/FT: BRNO CZ 98 .270 Win
The pictures don't do this rifle justice. Not a scratch on it. Ceracote is perfect and the wood is beautiful. If you don't know much about BRNO CZ see below.
BRNO CZ 98 is a bolt-action carbine designed and produced in Czechoslovakia from 1924 to 1942. It was developed from the famous Mauser Gewehr 98 line, and features a very similar bolt design. The rifle was designed in Czechoslovakia shortly after World War I, featuring a 600 mm (23.6") barrel which was shorter and considered more handy than the 150 mm (5.9") -longer Gewehr 98. The carbine followed a similar trend in weapon design at the time, that a short rifle gave away little in ballistic efficiency at combat ranges, but was easier to handle on account of its shorter length.During World War II, the BRNO CZ 98 was produced for the German armed forces during its occupation. The rifle was also produced in nearby Slovakia, a German ally and puppet state during the war.

title: For Sale:  Type 53 Mosin Nagant-FLAME THROWER
postcontent:
Type 53 (Chinese) Mosin Nagant
CHINESE FLAME THROWER!

I bought this gun and proceeded to tear it apart and restore it. Every piece has been checked for rust, function and appearance. I sanded down the stock, which needed much sanding. Then tung oiled it numerous times, then sealed with a satin finish, then applied 4 coats of Thompson’s Water Seal. The lower butt plate area has been repaired (see photos) but is a solid repair. Also, since I had to sand the hell out of it, the hand guard needed to be “bolstered” in order to be tight enough to retain the bands. So I fabricated two small dowels that fit were the cleaning rod would go (does not have cleaning rod) then to ensure a tight fit, added a plastic zip tie around hand guard. It is now very tight, and does not affect function whatsoever.

I went through all the metal and reblued using a cold blue, it is not 100% but looks very good. The bayonet is intact and functions perfectly. All the metal parts are 100% with absolutely no rust. The sling hardware has been polished and so has the hand guard metal. The butt plate has been highly polished by hand and now looks similar to chrome as well as the whole bolt assembly. Each piece of the bolt has been hand polished and is very smooth and very shiny, you could not tell it is over 57 years old (manufacturered in 1955). 

I cleaned out the chamber with a shotgun brush and steel wool, so that it would not have a sticky bolt issue...it works great. The chamber is very clean. The bore is very good with strong rifling and has NOT been counter bored. 

I bought an aftermarket sling (black, not green) as well as a cleaning kit and Mosin firing pin tool. Neither of these come with the Type 53, But they are included with mine.

Also include are 110 rounds of ammo, 90 of which are on stripper clips.

It also comes with an extra rubber butt plate to extend length of pull.

I have taken to the range to insure it is 100% functional and it shoots great.

Numbers DO NOT MATCH
